<DIV class=3D"post xfolkentry">
<H1><A class=3D"postheader taggedlink"=20
href=3D"http://idippedut.dk/post/2008/05/Document-translation-sucks-(When=
-Rob-is-right2c-hes-right).aspx">Document=20
translation sucks (When Rob is right, he's right)</A></H1>
<DIV class=3Ddescr>May 14, 2008 20:37 by <A=20
href=3D"http://idippedut.dk/author/jlundstocholm.aspx">jlundstocholm</A><=
/DIV>
<DIV class=3Dentry>It is very seldom I read one of <A=20
href=3D"http://www.robweir.com/blog/">Rob's posts</A> and think "That is =
just so=20
true" - but yesterday was one of those occasions. I was reading through =
<A=20
href=3D"http://www.robweir.com/blog/2008/05/spreadsheet-file-format-perfo=
rmance.html">his=20
latest post about load of different documents in a couple of =
applications</A>=20
and I couldn't help but smile when I got to the part where Rob made som=20
observations about possible reasons for the poor load times of ODF-files =
using=20
Microsoft Office 2003:<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>What is a file filter? It is like 1/2 of a translator. =
Instead of=20
  translating from one disk format to another disk format, it simply =
loads the=20
  disk format and maps it into an application-specific memory model that =
the=20
  application logic can operate directly on. This is far more efficient =
than=20
  translation. This is the untold truth that the layperson does not =
know. But=20
  this is how everyone does it. That is how we support formats in =
SmartSuite.=20
  That is how OpenOffice does it. And that is how MS Office does it for =
the file=20
  formats they care about. In fact, that is the way that Novell is now =
doing it=20
  now, since they discovered that the Microsoft approach is doomed to=20
  performance hell.<BR></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>I have been trying to pitch my idea of "document format channels" =
for=20
some time now. The basic idea is not to do translations between formats =
but to=20
support the feature sets of both formats in the major applications. </P>
<P>I remember when I participated in the <A=20
href=3D"http://idippedut.dk/post/2007/11/What-is-a-conversion2c-really.as=
px">interop-work=20
for the Danish Government in Fall 2007</A> and we tried to say something =
clever=20
about the dissapointing results we saw of translation, we heard the =
rumours of=20
Novell skipping the XSLT-translation of ODF to OOXML (and vice versa) =
and=20
instead extend the internal object model of Novell's edition of =
OpenOffice.org .=20
This was there the idea was born. </P>
<P>The idea was to round-trip documents in the format they were born and =
not to=20
attempt translation (also, how the hell do you translate e.g. a digital=20
signature between an ODF-file and an OOXML-file?).&nbsp; What triggered =
the=20
"vision" was that 1) the formats are not fully compatible and 2) =
translation=20
sucks. In every interop-session I have attended and in every piece of=20
interop-work I have participated in, there has been one, crystal clear=20
conclusion: </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>When you translate, you loose information. </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Essentially, translation is a poor-man's document consumption, =
because if you=20
loose information when translating - why would do it? As Rob so =
correctly points=20
out - when Microsoft chooses to use translators to enable "support" for =
ODF in=20
their Microsoft Office suites, it's really another way of saying: "We =
don't=20
really care about ODF". The same thing naturally goes for OpenOffice.org =
(and=20
spin-offs). When they insist of implementing just import filters for =
OOXML and=20
use translators to do so - they are saying exactly the same: "We don't =
really=20
care about OOXML". In both cases what they are communicating to their =
users is=20
really </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>We don't care that you loose information - you'll just have to =
settle for=20
  half of the correct solution </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>It's the same message I hear when some of my colleagues come to me =
and say:=20
"Jesper, I finished the piece of code you wanted me to do". Sometimes I =
am=20
blessed with conversations like: </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>Colleage: I finished the code piece<BR>Jesper: Cool - does it work =
all=20
  right?<BR>Colleage: Eh well, it compiles just fine ... =
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Is that good enough? </P>
<P>(and with this friendly post, I can only hope "someone" will accept =
the=20
LinkedIn-invitation I sent in February just before the BRM in Geneva ... =
or=20
maybe I should try <A=20
href=3D"http://www.diigo.com/profile/jlundstocholm">Diigo</A> instead?) =
</P>
<P><IMG title=3DSmile alt=3DSmile=20
src=3D"http://idippedut.dk/admin/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/images/smiley-=
smile.gif"=20
border=3D0> </P><BR></DIV>
