<P class=3Dcontent>I think its important that all vendors should support =
the major=20
document formats available. Perhaps its about time Microsoft finally =
wakes up=20
and provides "choice" to its customers by supporting ODF in its =
products. They=20
already have native support for "inferior" file formats like HTML, RTF, =
CSV and=20
TXT. Why not ODF too? <BR><BR>yk.</P>
<P class=3Dauthor><A href=3D"http://www.openmalaysiablog.com/">Yoon-Kit =
Yong</A>=20
</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcomment id=3Did_ce376368-30b8-4c6e-b244-3e6bfa36f769>
<P class=3Ddate>May 15. 2008 12:38</P>
<P class=3Dgravatar><IMG alt=3D"Luc Bollen"=20
src=3D"http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=3D7d7727c2379a899b5=
850369094f14b79&amp;size=3D80&amp;default=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fidippedut.dk%2fm=
onster.axd%3fseed%3d7d7727c237%26size%3d80"></P>
<P class=3Dcontent>@Jesper: <BR><BR>"The same thing naturally goes for=20
OpenOffice.org (and spin-offs). When they insist of implementing just =
import=20
filters for OOXML and use translators to do so - they are saying exactly =
the=20
same" <BR>To my knowledge, OpenOffice.org uses an import filter for =
OOXML (as=20
you mentioned), *not* a translator. <BR><BR>"When Microsoft chooses to =
use=20
translators to enable "support" for ODF in their Microsoft Office =
suites, it's=20
really another way of saying: "We don't really care about ODF"." <BR>In =
fact,=20
Microsoft is not even using ODF translators in MS Office: they simply =
fund a=20
stand alone translator project. My interpretation is not that MS says =
"We don't=20
care about ODF", they really says "Go to hell, ODF". <BR><BR>Microsoft =
claims=20
for a year that they want an ISO stamp for OOXML "to offer choice of =
format to=20
the users", but their acts clearly tell the true story: they really want =
to=20
*prevent* choice of format. <BR><BR>If OpenOffice.org is able in a quite =
short=20
timeframe to have an import filter for OOXML (while claiming that users =
don't=20
need a second ISO format), how come that MS has not been able in more =
than 2=20
years since ISO acceptance of ODF, to include an import filter in MS =
Office=20
(while claiming that they want to provide a choice of ISO formats) ? =
<BR></P>
<P class=3Dauthor>Luc Bollen </P></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"comment self" =
id=3Did_c2931275-7eb3-4568-a091-0c53481ce58b>
<P class=3Ddate>May 15. 2008 13:49</P>
<P class=3Dgravatar><IMG alt=3Djlundstocholm=20
src=3D"http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=3D1d5ec54ff1560794a=
ca49a5c05f5d028&amp;size=3D80&amp;default=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fidippedut.dk%2fm=
onster.axd%3fseed%3d1d5ec54ff1%26size%3d80"></P>
<P class=3Dcontent>Luc, <BR><BR><CITE title=3DQuote>To my knowledge, =
OpenOffice.org=20
uses an import filter for OOXML (as you mentioned), *not* a =
translator.</CITE>=20
<BR><BR>The difference is subtle. The point I am trying to make is that =
we need=20
full support for the formats - regardless of the import mechanism. Using =
a=20
translator is a bad idea since it is error-prone and information gets =
lost.=20
Using a filter but without adequate enhancement of the internal object =
model of=20
the consuming application is almost just as bad - you just arrive at a =
crappy=20
document a bit sooner because of the faster load time. <BR><BR><IMG =
class=3Dflag=20
alt=3DSmile=20
src=3D"http://idippedut.dk/admin/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/images/smiley-=
smile.gif">=20
<BR><BR><CITE title=3DQuote>If OpenOffice.org is able in a quite short =
timeframe=20
to have an import filter for OOXML (while claiming that users don't need =
a=20
second ISO format), how come that MS has not been able in more than 2 =
years=20
since ISO acceptance of ODF, to include an import filter in MS Office =
(while=20
claiming that they want to provide a choice of ISO formats) ?</CITE>=20
<BR><BR>Please - have you tested the OOXML-import feature of OOo? it =
doesn't=20
even come close to being usable. To talk about "in a quite short =
timeframe to=20
have an import filter for OOXML" is rather pointless. I believe that OOo =

themselves have labeled the import filter as "experimental".</P>
<P class=3Dauthor><A href=3D"http://idippedut.dk/">jlundstocholm</A> =
</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcomment id=3Did_a9876be8-2b64-49ca-9445-a88a564fe638>
<P class=3Ddate>May 15. 2008 17:13</P>
<P class=3Dgravatar><IMG alt=3D"Luc Bollen"=20
src=3D"http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=3D7d7727c2379a899b5=
850369094f14b79&amp;size=3D80&amp;default=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fidippedut.dk%2fm=
onster.axd%3fseed%3d7d7727c237%26size%3d80"></P>
<P class=3Dcontent>@Jesper: "have you tested the OOXML-import feature of =
OOo? it=20
doesn't even come close to being usable." <BR><BR>Of course, the quality =
of the=20
OOo filter is low: <BR>- OOo3 is still beta, <BR>- the OOXML =
specification=20
itself is still quite "experimental". Two and a half month after the =
BRM,=20
Microsoft, Ecma and ISO are still busy reshuffling the chapters and =
including=20
more than 1000 changes in it (have you heard anything about a release =
date?).=20
<BR>- in addition, OOXML was definitely not designed to ensure that MS=20
competitors will be able to easily write good import/export filters. =
<BR><BR>The=20
point I was making is that OOo is already busy providing native support =
for=20
OOXML, even before the spec is available. While MS has still not =
*announced* any=20
native ODF support 3 years after the 1.0 spec has been published by =
OASIS and 2=20
years after it has been approved by ISO. <BR><BR>This being said, I =
agree with=20
the main point of your post: document translation sucks, and Microsoft =
knows=20
this perfectly. <BR></P>
<P class=3Dauthor>Luc Bollen </P></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcomment id=3Did_c946040c-f9fa-444e-a22f-8d548ba0c11f>
<P class=3Ddate>May 16. 2008 03:00</P>
<P class=3Dgravatar><IMG alt=3Dorcmid=20
src=3D"http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=3Dd3c4cdb15c832cfc7=
46367a033b0d356&amp;size=3D80&amp;default=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fidippedut.dk%2fm=
onster.axd%3fseed%3dd3c4cdb15c%26size%3d80"></P>
<P class=3Dcontent>Interesting. <BR><BR>NitPick: Uh, how do you =
translate a=20
digital signature on an ODF file onto a modified ODF file? I get your =
point,=20
since the signature can't survive a translation into any other format =
because=20
that changes the signed material, just as it can't survive editing of =
the same=20
one (the whole point of digital signatures). <BR><BR>By the way, at the =
Oslo=20
SC34 meeting there was a resolution that suggested DIS29500 final =
version was in=20
the hands of JTC1, and SC34 wanted copies as soon as possible in support =
of the=20
activities that were initiated on behalf of 29500. Do you have any =
information=20
on what the hold-up is?</P>
<P class=3Dauthor><A href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/">orcmid</A> =
</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcomment id=3Did_37bb6218-6c0f-473e-8b86-a610117960c2>
<P class=3Ddate>May 16. 2008 05:59</P>
<P class=3Dgravatar><IMG alt=3D"Yoon-Kit Yong"=20
src=3D"http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=3Dae4b1b1fe7e216f1c=
874b3be342dc427&amp;size=3D80&amp;default=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fidippedut.dk%2fm=
onster.axd%3fseed%3dae4b1b1fe7%26size%3d80"></P>
<P class=3Dcontent>Hal, <BR><BR>Ive actually asked the secretary of SC34 =
for this=20
file. This is the response so far: <BR><BR>&gt; The final text prepared =
by the=20
project editor has been submitted to ITTF. <BR>&gt; However, I was asked =
by ITTF=20
not to distribute it to the SC 34 members <BR>&gt; since the =
availability of the=20
slightly different version from the <BR>&gt; actually published version =
would be=20
confusing. <BR>&gt; <BR>&gt; ITTF informed me that the proof will be =
available=20
in a few weeks and I <BR>&gt; am intending to post the proof (after =
confirmation=20
by the project editor) <BR>&gt; on the SC 34 website as soon as it =
becomes=20
available. <BR><BR>Im not sure why there would be more than one version =
at this=20
stage in time. <BR><BR>yk.</P>
<P class=3Dauthor><A href=3D"http://www.openmalaysiablog.com/">Yoon-Kit =
Yong</A>=20
</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3D"comment self" =
id=3Did_26a23d67-6a0b-49d9-9ffa-095b85ac545d>
<P class=3Ddate>May 16. 2008 09:52</P>
<P class=3Dgravatar><IMG alt=3Djlundstocholm=20
src=3D"http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=3D1d5ec54ff1560794a=
ca49a5c05f5d028&amp;size=3D80&amp;default=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fidippedut.dk%2fm=
onster.axd%3fseed%3d1d5ec54ff1%26size%3d80"></P>
<P class=3Dcontent>orcmid, <BR><BR><CITE title=3DQuote>NitPick: Uh, how =
do you=20
translate a digital signature on an ODF file onto a modified ODF file? I =
get=20
your point, since the signature can't survive a translation into any =
other=20
format because that changes the signed material, just as it can't =
survive=20
editing of the same one (the whole point of digital signatures).=20
</CITE><BR><BR>(I assume you mean "digital signature on an OOXML file =
onto a=20
modified ODF file" or vice versa, right?) <BR><BR>The problem with =
translation=20
and digital signatures is that the verification chain gets destroyed =
when=20
translating a document. In quite a few government usages of documents =
the=20
change-log or "editorial process" of a round-tripped document is bound =
by legal=20
requirements to document on each step who changed what in the process. =
When=20
translating the document from ODF to OOXML the digital signature becomes =
moot=20
for the other participants in the process. <BR><BR>About DIS29500: I =
have no=20
solid information. As Yoon-Kit mentions, is is also my impression that =
IS29500=20
sits with ITTF, but I have no "proof" of that.</P>
<P class=3Dauthor><A href=3D"http://idippedut.dk/">jlundstocholm</A> =
</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcomment id=3Did_5fba7e76-2a4b-40ce-bac5-f35a8b0725ca>
<P class=3Ddate>May 16. 2008 17:52</P>
<P class=3Dgravatar><IMG alt=3Dorcmid=20
src=3D"http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=3Dd3c4cdb15c832cfc7=
46367a033b0d356&amp;size=3D80&amp;default=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fidippedut.dk%2fm=
onster.axd%3fseed%3dd3c4cdb15c%26size%3d80"></P>
<P class=3Dcontent>I meant digital signature on any file to the same or =
another=20
format. The only thing you can do to preserve a digital signature is =
copy a=20
file, no alteration, of format or content, preserves the signature. The =
only=20
solution in all cases is to resign the material. Likewise, in editing an =
signed=20
ODF document, only the last signature survives. <BR><BR>So the chain of=20
provenance and auditability depends on being able to preserve the old =
version=20
and somehow provide an attestation about the new version (1) being based =
on it,=20
and (2) being signed by whoever did it and also any cosigners of the=20
attestation. <BR><BR>I agree that any conversion of the format creates =
this=20
requirement when authenticity matters. This will also happen in archives =
and=20
when document formats are "upgraded" as necessary to be usable with =
future or=20
different software. (Even making a PDF in a government archive, for =
example, or=20
making a translation into another language, etc.) <BR><BR>With OPC, =
OOXML makes=20
it a little easier to establish this sort of thing and even carry =
attestations=20
as extra material, but in truth neither format seems to provide specific =

assistance for the preservation of a chain of authenticity in a =
collaborative=20
work or a reformatted/translated work. <BR><BR>All I am saying that even =
with a=20
channel model, as I understand it, where the input and output are in the =
same=20
format, any editing invalidates any pre-existing digital signature. =
<BR><BR>If=20
you mean that means the original in its original format is the only one =
that=20
should be considered authentic, I agree. This is a read-only case and =
probably=20
not one that we need require either translation or filtering for to =
accomplish=20
viewing. Maybe providing viewers is for different scenarios and use =
cases?=20
<BR><BR>Interesting topic. Thanks for bringing it up.</P>
<P class=3Dauthor><A href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/">orcmid</A> =
</P></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcomment id=3Did_b3ff4d39-c247-4168-9b9b-6ad831132fae>
<P class=3Ddate>May 16. 2008 22:46</P>
<P class=3Dgravatar><IMG alt=3DhAl=20
src=3D"http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=3D79a775c4230c545bc=
4ac2fae8f29d006&amp;size=3D80&amp;default=3Dhttp%3a%2f%2fidippedut.dk%2fm=
onster.axd%3fseed%3d79a775c423%26size%3d80"></P>
<P class=3Dcontent>Document translations sucks indeed and this was was =
one of the=20
the major reasons for supporting OOXML as 99% of existing documents can =
be=20
translated to OOXML with near perfection. <BR>Creating ODF without =
having=20
backwards compatibility with existing document in mind was a major =
mistake as it=20
is not what profeesional organizations want. For organizations migrating =
to a=20
new XML format will be a major hassle. You would not want extra problems =
in=20
translating documents to add to that hassle. </P>
<P class=3Dauthor>hAl </P></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcomment id=3Did_ab4b89a8-e9c2-40f4-bdb0-b2e04635e716>
